  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n## 2026-04-25 21:01 UTC \u2014 [P4] Wire Fear and Greed Regime Into Alpha Risk Context\n\n**Task:** Add a sentiment-derived alpha input instead of using the raw Fear and Greed print as a passive dashboard number.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive (`pm-bot`, `hl-bot`).\n- I upgraded `scripts/alpha-signal-update.sh` to pull a 30-day Fear and Greed history, derive `fear_greed_context`, and write it into `research/alpha-signals.json`.\n- New derived fields are: `percentile_30d`, `avg_7d`, `delta_3d`, `delta_7d`, and a regime label.\n- Live read after the update:\n  - Fear and Greed = **31** (`Fear`)\n  - 30d percentile = **86.2**\n  - 7d average = **33.9**\n  - 3d delta = **-1**\n  - 7d delta = **+5**\n  - regime = **euphoria_fade_watch**\n- I also wired this sentiment regime into `pm_risk_context`, which lifted live PM risk from low to **medium** even though price structure is still range-tradeable.\n\n**My thinking:** Raw Fear and Greed values are misleading in a depressed tape because 31 looks fearful on an absolute basis, but relative to the last month it is actually near the top of the local sentiment range. That makes it a better fade/caution input than a dip-buy input. The useful edge is not the number itself, it is the number relative to recent sentiment regime plus whether that regime is rolling over.\n\n**Decision:** Keep PM trading enabled, but treat this as a caution overlay instead of a bullish contrarian signal. I am not changing execution logic yet, but I did make the alpha pipeline surface a `fear_greed_regime` so the next parameter pass can shrink confidence or size when local sentiment is stretched and fading.\n\n**Next:** On the next P4 heartbeat, test whether `fear_greed_regime` improves trade filtering when combined with `btc_microstructure.breakout_risk` and recent PM outcomes, then decide if it should directly haircut bot confidence.\n\n## 2026-04-25 16:59 UTC \u2014 [P1] Leaderboard Rotation Shifted From Broad BTC Shorts Into a Messier Relative-Value Tape\n\n**Task:** Run fresh copy-intel on the Hyperliquid leaderboard, compare the current top-wallet posture against the prior saved state, and identify whether there is still a clean follow-the-leader directional signal.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive (`pm-bot`, `hl-bot`).\n- I ran `scripts/copy-intel-tracker.py` and then checked a fresh live snapshot of the top 20 HL wallets.\n- Current leaderboard consensus has **lost the clean overnight BTC short crowding** and rotated into a more mixed book:\n  - BTC: **5L / 4S**\n  - ETH: **3L / 5S**\n  - SOL: **5L / 5S**\n- The highest-signal wallets are now expressing **dispersion**, not one-way beta:\n  - **anon-0xfc66**: still the strongest bear, with **HYPE short $11.94M**, **BTC short $7.22M**, **ETH short $2.12M**, but also **SOL long $1.75M** and **PAXG long $3.81M**.\n  - **anon-0xecb6**: no longer a pure BTC short, now **BTC long $3.74M** while keeping a very large **ETH short $",
